This taxonomy defines the content taught in each grade. Every once in a while you might find a link as source of the information found, IGNORE IT.

1º ESO (1st Year of ESO, ~12-13 years old)
Natural Numbers (Números naturales): Decimal numeration system and place value; rounding and estimating natural numbers; properties of operations (commutative, associative, distributive laws); exponentiation (powers of natural numbers and base 10, scientific notation); square roots; order of operations; reading and writing Roman numerals. matematicastro.esrecursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Divisibility (Divisibilidad): Factors and multiples; divisibility rules/criteria; prime and composite numbers; prime factorization; greatest common divisor (GCD) and least common multiple (LCM); solving problems using GCD and LCM. matematicastro.esmatematicastro.es.


Integers (Números enteros): Introduction to negative numbers and the set of integers; comparing and ordering integers; addition and subtraction of integers (using number line, rules for signs); multiplication and division of integers; combined operations with integers; applications of integers in real contexts (temperature changes, money gains/losses). matematicastro.esmatematicastro.es.


Fractions (Fracciones): Understanding fractions as part of a whole or ratio; equivalent fractions and simplifying fractions; comparing fractions; addition and subtraction with like and unlike denominators (finding common denominators); multiplication and division of fractions; mixed numbers and improper fractions; combined operations with fractions in calculations. matematicastro.esmatematicastro.es.


Decimals (Números decimales): Decimal place value and decimal fractions; converting between fractions and terminating or repeating decimals; rounding decimals; addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division with decimals; word problems involving decimals (e.g. money and measurements).


Metric System (Sistema Métrico Decimal): Units of length, mass, and capacity (meter, liter, gram, etc.) and their prefixes; converting between units (e.g. cm to m, kg to g); understanding and computing with compound units; word problems involving measurements and unit conversions.


Direct Proportionality and Percentages (Proporcionalidad directa y porcentajes): Concept of ratio and proportion; identifying directly proportional magnitudes; solving “rule of three” problems; basic percentages (calculate a percentage of a quantity, percentage increase or decrease). matematicastro.es.


Introduction to Algebra (Introducción al álgebra): Using variables and algebraic symbols; writing and simplifying algebraic expressions; monomials and basic operations with monomials; understanding equations vs. identities; solving simple first-degree (linear) equations (including those with fractions) and applying equations to solve word problems. matematicastro.es.


Lines and Angles (Rectas y ángulos): Basic geometry concepts – types of lines (parallel, perpendicular) and segments; types of angles (acute, right, obtuse, straight); measuring angles with a protractor; adjacent and vertical angles; introduction to angle relationships.


Polygons and Circumference (Figuras geométricas planas y circunferencia): Classification of polygons by number of sides; regular vs. irregular polygons; properties of triangles and quadrilaterals; parts of a circle (radius, diameter, circumference); perimeter of polygons and circumference length formula; interior and exterior angles of simple polygons.


Area of Plane Figures (Perímetros y áreas de figuras planas): Calculating area for basic figures – square, rectangle, triangle, parallelogram, trapezoid, regular polygons, and circle; using formulas for area; composite area problems; problem-solving involving perimeter and area. recursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Geometric Solids (Cuerpos geométricos): Recognizing 3D shapes (prisms, pyramids, cylinders, cones, spheres); elements of polyhedra (faces, edges, vertices); nets of polyhedra; surface area of cubes and rectangular prisms; volume of solids like cubes, rectangular prisms and basic cylinders; solving problems with volume and surface area.


Functions and Graphs (Funciones y gráficas): Concept of a function as a dependence between two quantities; Cartesian coordinate system (x–y plane); plotting points; interpreting simple linear relationships; constructing tables of values; graphing linear functions (proportional relationships). recursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Statistics and Probability (Estadística y probabilidad): Statistics: Collecting and organizing data; frequency tables; calculating measures of central tendency (mean, median, mode) and range; representing data in bar charts, line graphs or pie charts. Probability: Basic idea of probability as chance; simple probability of an event (favorable outcomes vs. total outcomes) with experiments like flipping a coin or rolling dice; understanding probability as a fraction or percentage. recursos.edu.xunta.gal.


(Sources: The above topics for 1º ESO are covered by standard Spanish math textbooks recursos.edu.xunta.galrecursos.edu.xunta.gal, including natural number arithmetic, fractions, basic geometry, introduction to algebra, functions, and an initiation to statistics/probability.)
2º ESO (2nd Year of ESO, ~13-14 years old)
Integers and Introduction to Rational Numbers (Números enteros y racionales): Review and extension of integers; absolute value and opposites; the concept of rational numbers (introducing negative fractions/decimals); properties of operations with integers and rational numbers; power and root operations with integers (including negative bases); scientific notation for large/small numbers. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Fractions and Rational Number Operations (Fracciones): Deeper practice with fractions and rational numbers – equivalent fractions, simplification; addition, subtraction, multiplication, division of fractions (including mixed numbers); converting between fractions and decimals (terminating and recurring decimals); problem solving with fractions in various contexts. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Powers and Square Roots (Potencias y raíz cuadrada): Laws of exponents (product, quotient, power of a power); computing powers and square roots; perfect squares and estimating non-perfect square roots; introduction to negative exponents (to represent fractions); scientific notation revisited; operations with powers and roots in expressions. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Decimals (Números decimales): Operations with decimals (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) with increased complexity; rounding and precision; converting repeating decimals to fractions; word problems involving decimals (e.g. currency, measurements).


Algebraic Expressions (Expresiones algebraicas): Introduction to algebraic language – variables, coefficients, terms; simplifying algebraic expressions (combine like terms, remove parentheses); operations with monomials and simple polynomials; evaluating expressions for given values of variables.


Equations (Ecuaciones de primer y segundo grado): Solving first-degree (linear) equations in one variable (including with fractional coefficients and parentheses); solving simple quadratic equations (second-degree) by factorization or basic methods (incomplete quadratics); setting up equations from word problems and solving them.


Systems of Equations (Sistemas de ecuaciones): Solving systems of two linear equations in two unknowns (by substitution, elimination, graphing methods); interpreting the solution (unique solution, no solution, infinite solutions); applications of systems in problem situations (e.g. mixture problems, value/cost problems). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Direct and Inverse Proportionality (Proporcionalidad numérica): Understanding direct proportionality (linear relationships) and inverse proportionality; solving problems using the rule of three; ratio and proportion in various contexts; unit rates; percentage problems (increase, decrease, interest) as applications of proportionality. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Geometric Proportionality (Proporcionalidad geométrica): Similarity in geometry – concept of similar figures; scale factors; properties of proportions in similar triangles (basic introduction to Thales’ theorem); solving problems of indirect measurement using similarity (e.g. shadow problems).


Plane Figures and Area (Figuras planas y áreas): Review of 2D shapes (triangles, quadrilaterals, regular polygons, circles); calculating areas of complex figures (using composition and decomposition into known shapes); the Pythagorean theorem (as a tool for finding lengths in right triangles); problem solving involving perimeter, area, and the Pythagorean theorem.


3D Shapes and Surface Area (Cuerpos geométricos y áreas): Prisms, cylinders, pyramids, cones, spheres – identifying properties; calculating surface areas of prisms and cylinders (and other simple solids); nets of solids; problem solving with surface area (e.g. painting or wrapping a 3D object).


Volume of Solids (Volumen de cuerpos geométricos): Volume formulas for prisms and cylinders (and familiarity with volume of pyramids, cones, spheres conceptually); solving volume problems (including capacity units conversion); real-world problems involving volume (e.g. volume of liquid in a tank). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Introduction to Functions (Funciones): Understanding the notion of a function as a relation between two sets; independent and dependent variables; function notation; evaluating functions; linear functions and their graphs (y = mx + b form); proportional relationships as linear functions through the origin; interpreting graphs of real-life situations. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Statistics and Probability (Estadística y probabilidad): Statistics: collecting data and organizing it into frequency tables (with class intervals if needed); bar graphs, histograms, and pie charts; measures of central tendency (mean, median, mode) and measures of dispersion (range). Probability: experimental probability vs. theoretical probability; probability of single events; introduction to combined events (and/or cases for simple events); solving elementary probability problems (cards, dice, etc.). matematicasinclusivas.com.


(Sources: The topics for 2º ESO are confirmed by textbook indices matematicasinclusivas.com, including an emphasis on rational number operations, introductory algebra (expressions, equations, systems), proportionality, geometry of area and volume, and basic functions, statistics, and probability.)
3º ESO (3rd Year of ESO, ~14-15 years old)
(In 3º ESO, all students follow a common curriculum, though some materials differentiate “Matemáticas Académicas” vs. “Aplicadas” with similar core content.)
Rational Numbers (Fracciones y decimales): Comprehensive work with rational numbers in fractional and decimal form; operations with fractions (reinforcing 2º ESO content at a more advanced level); operations with decimals (including more complex repeating decimal conversions); ordering and comparing rational numbers; problem solving with ratios and proportional reasoning. recursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Powers and Roots (Potencias y raíces): Exponent rules with positive and negative exponents; scientific notation and significant figures; square and cube roots; introduction to irrational numbers via non-perfect roots (e.g. √2); operations with powers and roots in algebraic contexts; problem solving requiring exponent manipulation. youtube.comrecursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Arithmetic Problem Solving (Problemas aritméticos): Tackling multi-step arithmetic problems that involve ratios, percentages, and proportional reasoning; direct and inverse proportionality in complex contexts; word problems combining concepts of fractions, decimals, percentages (e.g. mixture problems, rate problems, financial math with discounts and interest).


Sequences and Progressions (Progresiones): Understanding number sequences; arithmetic progressions (common difference, n-th term formula, partial sum formula); geometric progressions (common ratio, n-th term, partial product); solving problems with sequences (finding terms, sums); recognizing simple patterns and series. matematicasinclusivas.comrecursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Algebraic Language and Polynomials (Lenguaje algebraico y polinomios): Using algebraic notation fluently; forming algebraic expressions from word statements; operations with polynomials (addition, subtraction, multiplication); special products (e.g. squaring a binomial, sum·difference); polynomial factoring introduction (common factor, simple cases); simplifying rational algebraic fractions (reduction).


Equations (Ecuaciones de 1º y 2º grado): Solving first-degree (linear) equations and inequalities (including with absolute value or fractional forms); solving quadratic equations (by factoring, completing the square, or quadratic formula as appropriate); problem solving by setting up equations or systems derived from real situations. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Systems of Equations (Sistemas de ecuaciones): Solving systems of linear equations (extended practice from 2º ESO) including word problems; introduction to systems of a linear and a quadratic equation (when part of curriculum); methods of solution (graphical, substitution, elimination) and interpreting results in context. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Functions and Graphs (Funciones y gráficas): Deepening understanding of functions; identifying linear vs. non-linear functions; the concept of slope and y-intercept for linear functions; graphing linear functions and determining equations from graphs; introduction to quadratic functions (parabolas) – basic shape and features; using tables, graphs, and formulas to represent functions. recursos.edu.xunta.gal.


Geometric Problem Solving in the Plane (Problemas métricos en el plano): Applying geometry to solve metric problems – perimeter and area review at greater depth; the Pythagorean theorem and its converse in complex figures; properties of similar triangles and the Thales’ theorem for indirect measurement problems; basic trigonometry introduction (relationships in similar right triangles: sine, cosine, tangent ratios) for finding lengths and angles.


Geometric Transformations and Similarity (Movimientos y semejanzas): (In some curricula, included in 3º ESO.) Understanding transformations: translations, rotations, reflections on the plane; properties of figures under transformations (congruence vs. similarity); formal treatment of similarity of polygons, especially triangles; solving problems involving scale drawings and maps due to similarity.


3D Geometry (Cuerpos geométricos): Volume and surface area of more complex solids (prisms, cylinders, cones, pyramids, spheres); using formulas for volume and area in problem contexts; understanding the concept of geometric locus for points in space (basic loci like the set of points equidistant from a point is a sphere, etc., if included).


Statistics (Estadística): Data analysis with larger datasets; constructing histograms and frequency polygons; measures of central tendency and dispersion (mean, median, mode, range, possibly variance/standard deviation introduction in a simple way); interpreting statistical results; detecting misinterpretation or bias in data presentations. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Probability (Probabilidad): Fundamental probability rules; sample space and events; probability of combined independent events (using multiplication rule) and mutually exclusive events (addition rule); simple examples of conditional probability in intuitive terms; probability distributions for simple random experiments; expected value in simple cases. matematicasinclusivas.com.


(Sources: Standard 3º ESO materials cover rational numbers and exponents, progressions, more advanced algebra (polynomials, quadratic equations), linear systems, introduction to linear/quadratic functions, and geometry, as well as statistics and probability. recursos.edu.xunta.galrecursos.edu.xunta.gal.)
4º ESO (4th Year of ESO, ~15-16 years old)
In 4º ESO, mathematics splits into two tracks: Academic Mathematics (Matemáticas Académicas, for students aiming for Bachillerato) and Applied Mathematics (Matemáticas Aplicadas, for vocational paths). Below are the contents for each track in Madrid (the academic track aligns with the national curriculum for “Matemáticas Orientadas a Enseñanzas Académicas” matematicasinclusivas.com, while the applied track aligns with “Matemáticas Orientadas a Enseñanzas Aplicadas” matematicasinclusivas.com).
4º ESO Academic Track – Matemáticas Académicas:
Real Numbers & Percentages (Números reales y porcentajes): The real number system (natural, integer, rational, irrational numbers); operations with real numbers; intervals on the number line; percentage calculations (increase/decrease, compound percentages); proportional reasoning and financial math applications (tax, discounts).


Powers, Radicals and Logarithms (Potencias y radicales; logaritmos): Exponent laws review; scientific notation and significant figures; square roots, cube roots and n-th roots; simplification of radical expressions; introduction to logarithms as the inverse of exponentiation; basic log rules; solving simple exponential and logarithmic equations (base 10 and base e if introduced).


Polynomials and Algebraic Fractions (Polinomios y fracciones algebraicas): Operations with polynomials (addition, subtraction, multiplication, polynomial long division); factorization techniques (common factor, difference of squares, trinomials, etc.); simplifying rational algebraic expressions (fractions with polynomials in numerator and denominator); solving equations that involve rational algebraic fractions (excluding advanced cases).


Equations and Inequalities (Ecuaciones e inecuaciones): Solving quadratic equations (via formula, factorization, completing square); solving rational and radical equations (simple cases, extraneous solutions awareness); solving linear and quadratic inequalities in one variable and representing solutions on a number line; simple systems involving equations and inequalities.


Systems of Equations and Inequalities (Sistemas de ecuaciones e inecuaciones): Solving systems of linear equations in two unknowns (reinforcement) and introduction to systems of three linear equations in three unknowns; solving simple systems consisting of a linear and a quadratic equation; solving systems of linear inequalities in two variables (graphical solution, understanding feasible region).


Plane Geometry: Area, Volume & Similarity (Áreas, volúmenes y semejanza): Advanced problems of plane geometry – area calculation for composite shapes; using the Pythagorean theorem and distance formulas; concepts of similarity in plane figures; area and volume scale factors under similarity; applications of similar triangles (Thales’ theorem) in indirect measurements; review of volume formulas for solids and solving complex volume problems (combining shapes).


Trigonometry: Definitions of sine, cosine, tangent for acute angles in right triangles; solving right triangles given certain sides/angles; working with the main trigonometric ratios; trigonometric problem solving in context (heights and distances); extending definitions to obtuse angles; basic trigonometric identities and formulas (e.g. sin²+cos²=1). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Vectors and Lines (Vectores y rectas): Introduction to vectors in the plane; vector representation (magnitude and direction); basic vector operations (addition, subtraction, scalar multiplication); equation of a line in the plane (slope-intercept form, point-slope form); relationships between lines (parallel, perpendicular conditions); solving geometric problems using vector methods (and understanding linear combination of vectors).


Functions: Deeper study of the concept of a function; types of functions (polynomial, rational, exponential, periodic/trigonometric); domain and range of a function; increasing/decreasing behavior; composite and inverse functions basics; problem solving using functional relationships; graphical interpretation of functional models. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Polynomial and Rational Functions (Funciones polinómicas y racionales): Analysis of polynomial functions (notably quadratic and cubic functions: roots, vertex, axis of symmetry for quadratics; end-behavior for higher degree); introduction to rational functions (simple cases like hyperbola y = k/x); asymptotes (vertical and horizontal); graph sketching of simple polynomial and rational functions.


Exponential and Trigonometric Functions (Funciones exponenciales y trigonométricas): Understanding the form of exponential growth/decay functions; basic properties of exponential functions and the number e (if included); logarithmic function as inverse of exponential (basic concepts); introduction to the sine and cosine functions as periodic functions (unit circle concept at a basic level); amplitude and frequency notions for trigonometric functions; sketching simple exponential and sinusoidal graphs.


Statistics (Estadística): One-variable (univariate) statistics recap and extension – frequency distributions, histograms; measures of central tendency and dispersion (mean, median, mode, range, and optionally variance/standard deviation basics); interpreting statistical results; possible introduction of bivariate data: scatter plots and correlation (if not left for Bachillerato).


Combinatorics (Combinatoria): Basic counting principles (addition and multiplication rules); permutations and combinations (simple cases) to count possible outcomes; solving combinatorial counting problems (often oriented toward calculating probabilities); factorial notation for counting arrangements. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Probability: Probability in multi-step experiments; use of combinatorics to compute probabilities in equiprobable cases; discrete probability distributions for simple cases; expectation value; classic probability problems (drawing cards, urn problems, etc.); understanding binomial probability in simple terms (introduction for later formal study). matematicasinclusivas.commatematicasinclusivas.com.


4º ESO Applied Track – Matemáticas Aplicadas:
Rational & Irrational Numbers (Números racionales e irracionales): Properties of rational numbers (fractions, decimals) and introduction to irrational numbers (e.g. √2, π) in a basic way; converting recurring decimals to fractions; real number line completeness intuition; practical calculations with rational approximations.


Numerical Proportionality (Proporcionalidad numérica): Direct and inverse proportionality applied to practical problems (rates, scales, map reading); extensive practice with percentages (including interest, profit/loss calculations); proportional reasoning in everyday contexts (recipes, unit conversions, etc.). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Polynomials: Basic operations with polynomials and algebraic simplifications needed in practical contexts; evaluating formulas; perhaps introduction to quadratic expressions factorable to aid in formula manipulations (less theoretical depth than academic track).


Equations and Systems (Ecuaciones y sistemas): Solving first-degree equations and simple quadratic equations as needed for applications; setting up equations from word problems; solving 2×2 linear systems of equations applied to real-life scenarios (like calculating costs, mixtures); emphasis on modeling situations with equations more than on formal solution methods proofs. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Perimeter, Area, and Volume (Perímetros, áreas y volúmenes): Practical geometry: calculating perimeters and areas of 2D figures (especially composite shapes relevant to real life, such as floor plans); surface area and volume of common 3D solids (prisms, cylinders, etc.); solving problems like material usage, capacity of containers, etc., with an emphasis on applying formulas correctly.


Similarity and Applications (Semejanza y aplicaciones): Understanding similarity and scale drawings; using proportionality and similarity in contexts like map scales, technical drawings, shadow problems; the Pythagorean theorem and basic trigonometry ratios for solving right-triangle problems (e.g. finding heights, distances). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Functions: Concept of function and its use in modeling (e.g. proportional relationships, cost and income functions); interpreting simple function graphs; linear functions (y = mx + b) and basic quadratic or exponential function examples in real contexts (growth of populations, etc.); using graphs to extract information about trends.


Graphs of Functions (Gráfica de una función): Plotting points and sketching the graph of a given function (especially linear and simple curves); reading and interpreting various real-world graphs (distance-time, speed-time, etc.); understanding slope as rate of change; problems that require drawing or using graphs for solutions.


Statistics and Probability (Estadística y probabilidad): Emphasis on descriptive statistics – organizing data into tables, calculating averages (mean, median, mode) and spread (range); interpreting data from graphs (bar graphs, pie charts); basic probability scenarios (dice, coins, simple lotteries) and calculating probabilities; understanding probability in everyday situations (like weather forecasts or risk). matematicasinclusivas.com.


(Sources: The 4º ESO academic track topics are confirmed by Santillana’s curriculum (e.g. including logarithms, trigonometry, vectors, combinatorics), while the applied track focuses on practical math (proportionality, basic algebra, and applied geometry). matematicasinclusivas.com.)
1º Bachillerato (1st Year of Bachillerato, ~16-17 years old)
In Bachillerato, students choose different modalities. The main math subjects are Matemáticas I (for Science/Technology track, sometimes called “Applied to Sciences”) and Matemáticas Aplicadas a las Ciencias Sociales I (for Social Sciences track). The content overlap is significant, with the Science track usually delving slightly deeper into theory (e.g. more emphasis on advanced algebra, function analysis, and calculus). Below are the typical topics for both:
Matemáticas I (Science/Technical track) – Key 1º Bachillerato Topics:
Real and Complex Numbers (Números reales): Review of real numbers and intervals; properties of absolute value and inequalities; introduction to complex numbers (definition of i, form a+bi, complex plane representation); basic operations with complex numbers (addition, multiplication). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Equations and Inequalities (Ecuaciones e inecuaciones): Solving a variety of equations: linear, quadratic (including use of quadratic formula), biquadratic, simple rational and radical equations; solving inequalities (linear and quadratic inequalities) and expressing solution sets in interval notation; systems of inequalities in one variable. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Systems of Equations (Sistemas de ecuaciones): Solving systems of linear equations (including 3 equations with 3 unknowns) using methods like substitution, elimination, and Cramer’s rule; discussion of consistency and number of solutions; solving simple nonlinear systems (e.g. a linear and a quadratic equation in two variables).


Trigonometry: Deep dive into trigonometric ratios and the unit circle; measuring angles in degrees and radians; definitions of sine, cosine, tangent for any angle (unit circle definitions); fundamental identities (e.g. sin²x + cos²x = 1) and basic trigonometric equations; solving oblique triangles using the Law of Sines and Law of Cosines; applications of trigonometry in geometry and real problems.


Complex Numbers (Números complejos): (Continued) Multiplication, division of complex numbers; complex conjugate; modulus and argument of a complex number; polar form of complex numbers (if included); solving quadratic equations with no real roots using complex numbers. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Analytic Geometry in the Plane (Geometría analítica): Coordinate geometry in 2D – equation of a line (slope-intercept form, general form, conditions for parallel/perpendicular); distance between points, midpoint formulas; equation of the circle; conic sections introduction (focus on analytical definition of parabola, ellipse, hyperbola and their standard equations). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Conic Sections (Cónicas): Detailed study of conics – parabola, ellipse, hyperbola: deriving and using their equations, key features (focus, directrix, axes, eccentricity in a basic sense); sketching these curves from equations; solving problems involving conic sections (e.g. reflective property of parabola qualitatively). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Functions: General properties of real functions – domain, range, zeros; parity (even/odd functions); symmetry; piecewise-defined functions; operations on functions (sums, composites, inverses); elementary functions studied include polynomial functions, rational functions, exponential and logarithmic functions, and basic trigonometric functions; applications of functions to model situations.


Limits and Continuity (Límites y continuidad): Concept of the limit of a function as x approaches a value (including infinity); calculating limits using algebraic simplification or notable limits (like $\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\sin x}{x}$); one-sided limits; infinite limits and vertical asymptotes; continuous functions and identifying discontinuities.


Differential Calculus – Derivatives (Derivadas): Definition of the derivative of a function (limit of incremental ratio); interpretation as slope of tangent and rate of change; basic differentiation rules (power rule, sum/difference rule, product and quotient rule, chain rule); derivatives of polynomial, exponential, logarithmic, and trigonometric functions (as applicable); finding equations of tangent lines. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Applications of Derivatives (Derivadas y funciones): Using the derivative for function analysis – finding critical points, increasing/decreasing intervals, local maxima and minima; second derivative and concavity; sketching graphs of functions using first and second derivative tests; optimization problems (max/min in economic or geometric contexts); related rates problems (if included). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Integral Calculus – Introduction (Integral indefinida): Understanding antiderivatives and indefinite integrals; basic integration rules (power rule in reverse, etc.); integration of simple functions (polynomials, basic exponentials, etc.); the constant of integration; simple differential equations by direct integration (if included).


Statistics (Estadística unidimensional): One-variable statistics revisited with more rigor – frequency distributions, cumulative frequency; measures of central tendency and dispersion with formulae (mean, weighted mean, variance and standard deviation); using statistical charts; understanding distributions (normal distribution introduction qualitatively).


Bivariate Statistics (Estadística bidimensional): Paired data analysis – scatter plots, correlation concept (positive, negative, none); line of best fit (by eye or least squares conceptually); linear regression basics; interpreting correlation coefficient (without deep calculation); two-variable frequency tables; marginal and conditional distributions.


Matemáticas Aplicadas CCSS I (Social Sciences track) – Key 1º Bachillerato Topics:
Real Numbers and Algebra Review: Real number properties, intervals, absolute value; proportional reasoning and percentages (reviewed in context of economics, social sciences applications). (Note: The social track often does not cover complex numbers in depth.)


Equations and Inequalities: Linear and quadratic equations; inequalities (emphasis on linear inequalities and simple quadratic inequalities) relevant to economic contexts (e.g. profit thresholds); basic systems of linear equations (with two or three unknowns) and their applications (supply/demand problems, etc.).


Financial Mathematics: (Often part of social math) Problems involving interest rates (simple and compound interest), percentages growth/decay, loan and amortization basics, which require setting up equations and understanding exponential growth (ties in with functions).


Trigonometry: Basics of trigonometry (if included) similar to Science track – right-triangle trigonometry and solving triangles, but with slightly less emphasis on theoretical identities and more on practical problem solving.


Analytic Geometry: Equations of lines and slope (important for cost/revenue linear models); introduction to conics is usually minimal for social track, possibly just basic parabola knowledge since quadratic functions are studied.


Functions: Emphasis on polynomial functions (linear and quadratic functions as models for data), simple exponential and logarithmic functions for modeling growth (population, finance); basic notion of elasticity in economics as an application of derivative is sometimes introduced; graph interpretation is heavily stressed (trend analysis). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Limits and Derivatives: Introduction to limits and continuity (conceptual understanding to support derivatives); definition of the derivative and basic derivative rules (power rule, etc.) focusing on polynomial and exponential models; applications of the derivative such as finding maxima/minima of a revenue or profit function, marginal analysis in economics (derivative as rate of change).


Graphing and Functions Analysis: Using derivatives to analyze and sketch functions (especially quadratic cost/revenue functions); understanding inflection qualitatively; optimization problems in economic contexts (maximize profit, minimize cost).


Integrals: Basic idea of the indefinite integral as antiderivative (social track often introduces integrals conceptually or very basically, possibly to connect area under curves with total values); not always a major emphasis in 1º Bach CCSS, but Santillana includes a unit on integrals, so simple integration of polynomials and its interpretation (area under rate function giving total change).


Statistics (Univariate and Bivariate): Strong focus on statistics for social sciences – interpreting data sets, calculating mean/median/mode and standard deviation; understanding indices (like CPI calculation, if included); bivariate data with correlation and linear regression (fitting a line to data, understanding slope and intercept in context); using correlation to draw conclusions (with caution about causation). matematicasinclusivas.com.


(Sources: The contents for 1º Bachillerato are drawn from Santillana’s official textbooks matematicasinclusivas.commatematicasinclusivas.com. Both the Science track and the Social Sciences track cover advanced algebra, analytic geometry, an introduction to calculus (limits, derivatives, basic integrals) and statistics, with the Social track placing more emphasis on applied topics like financial math and descriptive statistics.)
2º Bachillerato (2nd Year of Bachillerato, ~17-18 years old)
In the second year of Bachillerato, the math curriculum prepares students for university entrance exams. Matemáticas II is for Science/Engineering-oriented students, and Matemáticas Aplicadas a las CCSS II for Social Sciences. There is overlap in algebra and calculus, with divergence in geometry and statistical emphasis.
Matemáticas II (Science track) – Key 2º Bachillerato Topics:
Linear Algebra – Matrices and Determinants (Matrices y determinantes): Definition of matrices, matrix operations (addition, multiplication), the identity and inverse matrix; using matrices to solve linear systems (Gauss elimination basics); determinants of 2×2 and 3×3 matrices; properties of determinants; Cramer’s rule in solving systems. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Systems of Linear Equations: Advanced methods for solving linear systems (Gauss-Jordan elimination); discussion of solution spaces (unique solution, infinitely many, or none) using rank and determinant criteria; solving problems modeled by linear systems (e.g. intersection of planes, mixture problems with constraints).


Euclidean Geometry in Space (Vectores, rectas y planos en el espacio): Vectors in three-dimensional space; operations with 3D vectors; equations of lines and planes in space; relationships between lines and planes (parallelism, perpendicularity); calculating angles and distances in space (angle between two vectors, distance from point to plane, etc.). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Limits and Continuity: Rigorous work with limits of functions, including infinite limits and limits at infinity; determining asymptotes (horizontal, vertical, oblique); formal definition of continuity and classification of discontinuities; challenging limit computations (L’Hôpital’s rule may be introduced). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Differential Calculus – Derivatives: Differentiation of a wide variety of functions (polynomial, rational, exponential, logarithmic, trigonometric); higher-order derivatives; applying derivative tests for monotonicity and extrema; solving equations using derivatives (Newton’s method conceptually, perhaps); curve sketching combining all calculus information (critical points, inflection points, asymptotes).


Applications of Derivatives: In-depth optimization problems (geometric optimization, physics-related rates, economic optimization for science track context); related rates problems; use of derivatives in approximation (Taylor polynomial notion may be briefly mentioned); convexity and inflection points in graph analysis. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Integral Calculus: Indefinite integrals – integration techniques for standard forms (polynomial, simple rational functions, basic trig integrals); integration by parts and substitution (perhaps introduced at basic level); Definite integrals – definition via Riemann sums, the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus; computing areas under curves and between curves; solving area and volume problems by integration (rotation solids if included). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Probability and Statistics: Probability – combinatorics-based probability review; conditional probability and Bayes’ theorem; discrete random variables; the Binomial distribution and the Normal distribution as models; calculation of probabilities using distribution formulas or tables. matematicasinclusivas.com. Statistics – parameters of distributions (mean, variance of binomial, normal); using the normal distribution for approximations; inferential statistics introduction (confidence intervals, hypothesis testing basics) may be touched upon if time allows, but in Science track emphasis is often on probability theory rather than detailed statistical inference. (Note: In the Science track, more time is devoted to calculus and 3D geometry, while probability is covered sufficiently for the university entrance exam.)


Matemáticas Aplicadas CCSS II (Social Sciences track) – Key 2º Bachillerato Topics:
Matrices and Linear Systems: Basics of matrices (as for Science track, but focus on 2×2 and 3×3 cases); using matrices and determinants to solve linear systems of equations; emphasis on practical interpretation of solutions for economics (e.g. supply/demand equilibrium models). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Linear Programming (Programación lineal): Formulating linear programming problems (objective function, constraints); solving two-variable linear programming problems graphically – finding feasible region, corner-point principle; interpreting solutions (maximum profit, minimum cost). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Calculus (Limits and Derivatives): Understanding limits and continuity (conceptual, to support derivatives); differentiation of functions relevant to economics (polynomials, exponentials, logarithms); using derivatives to analyze marginal concepts (marginal cost, marginal profit); finding maxima/minima of functions (optimization of profit, revenue, cost functions). matematicasinclusivas.com.


Applications of Derivatives: Optimization in economic contexts (e.g. finding quantity that maximizes profit); elasticity of demand as an application of derivative; sketching graphs of key economic functions using calculus insights; understanding increase/decrease and concavity to interpret trends. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Integral Calculus: Introduction to integrals mainly for area under curve or accumulation function interpretation; basic antiderivatives of simple functions; definite integrals used to compute total growth or total cost from marginal functions; understanding consumer and producer surplus (as areas under curves) if included in curriculum. matematicasinclusivas.com.


Probability and Statistics: Probability – focus on probability distributions used in social sciences: Binomial distribution (for categorical data like surveys) and Normal distribution (as an approximation for many phenomena); calculating probabilities using the Binomial formula and Normal tables; understanding expectation and variance in context matematicasinclusivas.com. Statistics – Statistical inference is a key component: sampling methods, the concept of a sampling distribution; estimation of population parameters (mean, proportion) using confidence intervals; hypothesis testing basics (null and alternative hypotheses, significance level, p-value) especially for proportions or means in practical scenarios matematicasinclusivas.com. Also, regression and correlation analysis may be revisited with more data interpretation (for example, understanding the output of a linear regression in a social context).


(Sources: The 2º Bachillerato curriculum is detailed in official materials matematicasinclusivas.com. The Science track covers advanced calculus (integrals, series of calculus applications) and 3D geometry, while the Social Sciences track emphasizes linear programming, applied calculus, and a deeper focus on probability distributions and statistical inference matematicasinclusivas.commatematicasinclusivas.com.)
Each of the above topics comes with a variety of problem types – from routine skill practice (e.g. solving equations, simplifying expressions) to applied word problems (geometry problems, real-life scenarios in finance or science, data interpretation, etc.). The curriculum is designed to build from basic arithmetic in 1º ESO up to advanced concepts like calculus and statistics in Bachillerato, with problem-solving skills developed at every stage matematicasinclusivas.commatematicasinclusivas.com. The tags listed for each topic reflect the range of specific skills students practice, such as “derivatives – product rule” or “proportionality – rule of three,” ensuring that by the end of 2º Bachillerato, students have a comprehensive foundation in both pure and applied mathematics.
Sources: Official Spanish secondary math textbooks and curriculum outlines recursos.edu.xunta.galmatematicasinclusivas.com. These include Santillana’s Saber Hacer series (aligned with LOMCE/LOMLOE curricula in Madrid) and open educational resources like TutoMate and Marea Verde which detail each unit’s contents. The topics and problem types listed are consistent across major publishers (Anaya, SM, Santillana, etc.), covering all key areas from basic numeracy and algebra to geometry, calculus, and statistics as required in Spain’s ESO and Bachillerato programs.